         <h1>Boris Christoff, Bass, Dies at 79; Esteemed for His Boris Godunov </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Boris Christoff , the Bulgarian bass whose performances as Boris Godunov virtually defined the role for several generations of singers and operagoers , died yesterday at his home in Rome . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 79 . <br><blue>3</blue>The Associated Press reported the cause as the effects of a stroke he suffered six years ago . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Christoff 's insight into character and psychology made him one of the great acting singers of the century . <br><blue>5</blue>His voice was commanding more for its eloquence and color than for its size ; it was not enormous by the standards of the great Russian basses with whom he was usually compared ( most notably Chaliapin , whose successor he was often said to be ) , and the top had an almost baritonal brightness . <br><blue>6</blue>Yet he was able to produce the thundering rage necessary to play the aging , often mad kings in whom he specialized . <br><blue>7</blue>At the other end of the vocal spectrum , he was renowned for the kind of high , floated pianissimo that he brought to roles like Philip II in " Don Carlo . " <br><blue>8</blue>Above all , Mr. Christoff 's performances had an intensity of emotion and a deeply internalized sense of motivation . <br><blue>9</blue>On the opera stage -- and even on recordings -- his portrayals could be lifelike : sometimes terrifyingly , sometimes touchingly . <br><blue>10</blue>And although he created this effect most vividly in his performances of Russian operas and Verdi works , he brought a similarly colorful expressive range to the Russian song literature , which he helped restore to the active recital repertory . <br><blue>11</blue>Kings and Devils Mr. Christoff 's opera repertory included some 40 roles in 6 languages . <br><blue>12</blue>Notable among them , besides Mussorgsky 's Boris and Verdi 's Philip II , were Mephistopheles in Gounod 's " Faust , " several Wagner roles -- including Hagen in " Gotterdammerung " and King Marke in " Tristan und Isolde " -- and perhaps most curiously in the context of his other characters , the title role in Handel 's " Giulio Cesare . " <br><blue>13</blue>Mr. Christoff was born in Plovdiv , Bulgaria , on May 18 , 1914 , and earned a degree in law before he began studying music seriously . <br><blue>14</blue>During his student years , he was a member of the Gusla Choir , and in 1941 , when King Boris of Bulgaria heard him as a soloist with the ensemble , he was given a private stipend to support vocal studies in Italy . <br><blue>15</blue>He went to Rome to work with the bass Riccardo Stracciari , and also studied voice in Salzburg . <br><blue>16</blue>At the end of World War II , Mr. Christoff was interned in a displaced persons camp , and upon his release he returned to Rome . <br><blue>17</blue>He married there -- his wife , Franca , is his only survivor -- and made the city his home . <br><blue>18</blue>He made his professional concert debut there in 1946 as a soloist with the Academy of St. Cecilia Orchestra , and he made his operatic debut the same year , as Colline in " La Boheme " in a regional Italian house . <br><blue>19</blue>In 1947 he sang Pimen in " Boris Godunov " in Rome and at La Scala in Milan , and three years later Covent Garden engaged him to sing the work 's title role . <br><blue>20</blue>Boris soon became a signature role for him . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>Philip II</m_str> (7_27) 	<m_str>Verdi 's Philip II</m_str> (12_10) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>Rome</m_str> (1_30) 	<m_str>Rome</m_str> (19_12) 	<br><blue>3(1)</blue>: <m_str>1947</m_str> (19_2) 	<br><blue>4(8)</blue>: <m_str>King Marke in `` Tristan und Isolde ''</m_str> (12_35) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_52) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_2) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (13_23) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_6) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (14_25) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_33) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>his performances of Russian operas</m_str> (10_10) 	<m_str>Mr. Christoff 's performances</m_